# Chapter 7 — Macros

Macros are Scheme's superpower: user code that transforms code before the evaluator sees it. Sakura Scheme ships hygienic `syntax-rules` and the lower-level `define-macro`.

## `syntax-rules`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define-syntax swap!
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ a b) (let ((t a)) (set! a b) (set! b t)))))

(define x 1)
(define y 2)
(swap! x y)
(list x y)
</pre>

## `,expand`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
,expand (swap! foo bar)
</pre>

## `define-macro`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define-macro (unless test . body)
  `(if (not ,test) (begin ,@body) #f))

(unless (> 1 2) (display \"did not swap\")) (newline)
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> `,expand` is the fastest way to learn what a macro really does. Type `,expand (your-macro args…)` and you see the base forms it lowers to.

